:"Prussia, Germany","Rijnland, Preußen, Duitsland":"Rhineland, Prussia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes von Müllenark was born in 1134, in Müllenark, Inden, Düren, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany, her father, Gerhard I von Müllenark, was 29 and her mother, Mrs. Reginlinde Mullenark, was 24. She had at least 4 daughters with Hermann II. von Saffenberg. She died in 1180, in Rhineland, Prussia, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1134–1180":"1134–1180","1135–1206":"1135–1206","1138–1190":"1138–1190","1111–1172":"1111–1172","1158–1185":"1158–1185","1158–1201":"1158–1201","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","–Female":"Sur